    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-08-04T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-08-04T04:00:00-05:00" n="377"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d377">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00R294/865: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dodd</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-08-04T10:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 4, 1934—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 4—7:44 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>165. My 122, July [<hi rend="italic">June</hi>] 27, noon. Schroeder Banking
                    Corporation with cooperation of National City Bank submitted on August 1st to
                    Reichsbank a new concrete plan for solving transfer. Copy of plan <pb
                        facs="0582" n="482" xml:id="pg_482"/> shown Embassy involves an export
                    transaction of some magnitude which it is understood will be described directly
                    to the Department by Schroeder representative sent from New York next
                    Monday.</p>
                <p>Schroeder intimates Reichsbank well disposed toward plan but since the export
                    phase of transaction involved would bring little foreign exchange into Germany,
                    officials in Ministry of Economics are hesitating. Schroeder suggests that if
                    Department could express American Government’s approval of proposed solution and
                    authorize Embassy to intimate this to Foreign Office that competent German
                    authorities would probably concur in the plan and it could then be submitted for
                    initiating direct negotiations in accordance with your 49, April 14, 2 p.m.
                    Embassy understands plan includes extension of $2,000,000 credit to I. G.
                    Farben.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dodd</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
